(Loan Data From Prosper)¶

by (Rehab Emam)¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

Loan Data From Prosper This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others. (Last updated 03/11/2014)

Questions to pose:

  • What factors affect a loans outcome status?
  • Does the interest rate affect the borrower?
  • Are there differences between loans depending on how large the original loan amount was?

The dataset primarily overlook¶

The dataset has 113937 entries in rows with 81 features in columns.

From the dataset dictionary, So far, I see that LoanStatus, BorrowerRate,, LoanOriginalAmount, StatedMonthlyIncome, Term, ListingCategory, MonthlyLoanPayment, TotalProsperLoans, TotalProsperPaymentsBilled, and Occupation are features of interest in this dataset.

I'd like to see features that affect Loan completion rate, so I'll explore different features as BorrowerRate, Term, LoanOriginalAmount, MonthlyLoanPayment.

Univariate Exploration Conclusion¶

LoanStatus is my dependant variable, I want to see how different features affect it, whether BorrowerRate (interest rate), LoanOriginalAmount, Term or MonthlyLoanPayment. In numeric variables, I needed to scale plots to log scale, as all were right skewed. I see it's logic to have them right skewed with less points on bigger loans amounts. On Loan amounts, found some outliers around 35k.

All numeric variables I investigated were right skewed, I had to use a log scale to get a better look in their majority distributions.

I had to divide the dataset based on LoanStatus, whether completed or anything else, to see different features and their relation with completion of a loan.

Bivariate Exploration¶

<Figure size 720x360 with 0 Axes>
  • BorrowerRate has multimodal distribution with LoanStatus in most categories.
  • LoanOriginalAmount has average low amount but right-skewed
  • Same for MonthlyLoanPayment
  • StatedMonthlyIncome seems it has outliers due to high range of values, I had to scale it but still skewed.
  • Most loans seem to concentrate on the same term value.

The 2 categories that have real problems are 'Defaulted' and 'Chargedoff' are right skewed with higher interest rates.

I had to scale the monthly income so that I get a deeper look on relationship between MonthlyLoanPayment and StatedMonthlyIncome , a slight positive but not strong one.

Bivariate Conclusions¶

As my point of interest is completion of a loan, I tried to see relationships between loan status and different features I saw relevant as Loan amount, interest rate, individuals income and monthly payments.

Comparing Loanstatus categories against BorrowerRate , I saw completed and current loans have lower average interest rate than all other status categories. Also defaulted and chargedoff loans have skewness towards higher interest rates. so far I see BorrowerRate is an independant feature for loan status.

Comparing Loanstatus categories against LoanOriginalAmount, surprisingly I didn't see a good relationship between the loan amount and completion or not status, however, defaulted and chargedoff categories seem to have same relationships with loan amount.

Comparing Loanstatus categories against MonthlyLoanPayment, I notice lots of outliers on high monthly payments given loans are completed, although all categories have mean monthly payments around 250.

Comparing MonthlyLoanPayment and StatedMonthlyIncome, not much to state other than a slight positive relationship between them.

While working with the features I found relevant, I saw that combining StatedMonthly Income with MonthlyLoanPayment would be a good point to explore.

Feature Engineering¶

As a further exploration, I'll add a new variable by multiplying the monthly payments times number of months to get the generated loan amount after interests and fees, and see if it has a relationship with loan status.

In [53]:
df['LoanGenerated'] = df['Term'] * df['MonthlyLoanPayment']
plt.figure(figsize=[15,8]);
g = sb.FacetGrid(data=df, col='LoanStatus', margin_titles=True, height=3, col_wrap=4);
g.map(plt.scatter, 'BorrowerRate','LoanGenerated');
g.set_titles('{col_name}');

<Figure size 1080x576 with 0 Axes>

So far the relationship is strong between loan completion and interest rate and monthly payments.

Conclusion¶

  • After analysing pairs and more variables together, I can see that interest rate (BorrowerRate) is an influencial featute that affects the loan status, a range of 0.1-0.3 is a reasonable interest rate for completing a loan payment.
  • Also the Term feature has majority loans in one value (36 months).
  • I struggled a bit on LoanOriginalAmount, so I used feature engineering to create a new variable that has monthly payments multiplied by number of months , to get the total generated loan amountn paid, at that point, I could wrap the features together to realize that the generated loan amount affects the loan status, higher it is, gives a low completion rate.
  • Concluding that lowering the fees and interest rates give higher loan payment completion.
